Great post, Gerald. You are right that the term originated during the Korean war and has since come to refer to Asians of all nationality. During the great dispute over the Wall, it had been applied to Maya Lin on more than one occasion. During the Vietnam war it was used to demonize and depersonalize the enemy, thus allowing it easier to kill. This was/is the same in any war. I have always found it very offensive, especially since I had adopted a Korean born child. I take it as a personal affront.<br><br>
I wish I could swear that Tom is correct in the ascertion that there was no racism in &quot;combat units&quot;. Having served in a combat unit, there was no place for it, the dependence on each other didn't allow it. But, also, I understand that the war lasted ten years and I was only a small part of it. I have heard stories about units towards the tail end of the war, but, again, these are only stories. I truely do not know! 
